1. Question Could anyone recommend a useful method for approaching the following series? $$\sum_{k=2}^{\infty}\zeta'(k)x^{k-1}$$ Where $\zeta(z)$ is the Riemann Zeta function. I've seen that there are many series involving this function, but I haven't found any that involve its derivative, the analogue to this series without the derivative is $$\sum_{k=2}^{\infty}\zeta(k)x^{k-1}=-\gamma-\psi(1-x)$$ which has a closed form solution, I was curious to know if there was a closed form for the version with the derivative too Any suggestions are welcome Update I arrived at this formulation: $$\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}\zeta'\left(night)x^{n-1}=-\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}\sum_{k=1}^{\infty} rac{\ln\left(night)}{k^{n}}x^{n-1}=-\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\sum_{n=2}^{\infty} rac{\ln\left(night)}{k^{n}}x^{n-1}= rac{1}{x}\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}	ext{Li}_{0}^{\left(1,0ight)}\left( rac{x}{k}ight)$$ Where: $$	ext{Li}_{0}^{\left(1,0ight)}\left(zight):=\left. rac{\partial}{\partial 
u}	ext{Li}_{
u}\left(zight)ight|_{
u=0}=-\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\ln\left(kight)z^{k}$$ So $$\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}\zeta'\left(night)x^{n-1}= rac{1}{x} rac{\partial}{\partial 
